WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.000
Please join me in welcoming Namita Nandakumar.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:15.360
Alright, thanks everyone.

00:00:15.360 --> 00:00:17.520
It's exciting to be here.

00:00:17.520 --> 00:00:23.040
So Danny was a great lead into this because he works in hockey and was talking about football,

00:00:23.040 --> 00:00:27.920
and I work in football, and I'm going to talk about hockey.

00:00:27.920 --> 00:00:30.719
Just to give you a bit of background, I'm a quantitative analyst with the Philadelphia

00:00:30.719 --> 00:00:37.520
Eagles, but I also have done a lot of public hockey research in the past.

00:00:37.520 --> 00:00:42.599
To be honest, a lot of my public research is like really niche stuff about the draft

00:00:42.599 --> 00:00:44.820
that frankly none of you need to hear right now.

00:00:44.820 --> 00:00:52.279
So I thought that it would be maybe more interesting to learn about one of the most popular stats

00:00:52.279 --> 00:00:54.279
in public hockey analytics today.

00:00:54.279 --> 00:00:58.639
So that's expected goals, which is why the title is Finding Expected and Unexpected Goals

00:00:58.639 --> 00:00:59.639
with R.

00:00:59.639 --> 00:01:08.120
Just to give you guys a bit of background, there might not be some sports fans in here,

00:01:08.120 --> 00:01:12.400
but this definition worked really well the last time I used it at a technical conference,

00:01:12.400 --> 00:01:14.400
so I'm going to keep with it.

00:01:14.400 --> 00:01:17.120
Violent soccer on ice.

00:01:17.120 --> 00:01:23.000
And there are 31, soon to be 32, as Danny knows, teams in the NHL who spend all year

00:01:23.320 --> 00:01:28.440
trying to be good enough at violent soccer on ice that they win the Stanley Cup.

00:01:28.440 --> 00:01:29.440
Why does it matter?

00:01:29.440 --> 00:01:30.440
I don't know.

00:01:30.440 --> 00:01:31.959
Some people think it's fun.

00:01:31.959 --> 00:01:34.239
There are literally dozens of us who love it.

00:01:34.239 --> 00:01:40.000
So that's really the motivation here.

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:43.800
And so we can start to think about what are some ways to evaluate hockey teams and players.

00:01:43.800 --> 00:01:50.000
Maybe the most obvious one is the percentage of times that they win hockey games.

00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:51.559
That seems relevant.

00:01:51.559 --> 00:01:55.199
But also, in order to win games, you need to score more goals than your opponent.

00:01:55.199 --> 00:01:58.559
So goals for, goals against also seems valid.

00:01:58.559 --> 00:02:01.959
In order to score a goal, you need to take a shot.

00:02:01.959 --> 00:02:02.959
What's that saying?

00:02:02.959 --> 00:02:04.639
You miss 100% of the shots you don't take.

00:02:04.639 --> 00:02:08.520
So you can look at shots for and shots against.

00:02:08.520 --> 00:02:10.839
You could also just rely on your personal feelings.

00:02:10.839 --> 00:02:14.440
I think that that is equally valid, so I just wanted to put that up there.

00:02:14.440 --> 00:02:21.039
But since we are at an R conference, let's talk about the statistical aspect.

00:02:21.039 --> 00:02:26.440
So shots for and shots against have this really nice property for analytical purposes

00:02:26.440 --> 00:02:28.639
of being one of the most granular things we can observe.

00:02:28.639 --> 00:02:35.000
If there are five, six, seven goals in a game, there are dozens of shots that we can look

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:36.000
at.

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:41.759
But the natural retort to this, which has been true for years, as long as people have

00:02:41.759 --> 00:02:48.039
evaluated shot-based metrics, is that not all shots are equally dangerous.

00:02:48.039 --> 00:02:49.039
And that's right.

00:02:49.039 --> 00:02:51.240
We have a right to criticize that.

00:02:51.240 --> 00:02:55.440
And so that begs the question, what are the other features that we can account for in

00:02:55.440 --> 00:02:58.320
hockey analytics?

00:02:58.320 --> 00:02:59.520
And so let's take a look.

00:02:59.520 --> 00:03:02.800
So I wanted to give you guys a little visual here.

00:03:02.800 --> 00:03:07.160
So this is a goal that happened recently.

00:03:07.160 --> 00:03:11.520
Again, we're starting from the basics here.

00:03:11.520 --> 00:03:16.279
And to give you a little bit of a closer look at this goal, again, this is a randomly chosen,

00:03:16.279 --> 00:03:17.279
it's not really random.

00:03:17.279 --> 00:03:18.279
I'm from Philly.

00:03:18.520 --> 00:03:21.639
I'm a Flyers fan, so this is a Flyers goal.

00:03:21.639 --> 00:03:22.639
From this season.

00:03:22.639 --> 00:03:25.360
So it happened a couple weeks ago.

00:03:25.360 --> 00:03:34.240
And it's worth trying to figure out what can we say and what can't we say about this goal.

00:03:34.240 --> 00:03:41.520
So just by looking at the play-by-play data, we know that it was, in fact, a goal.

00:03:41.520 --> 00:03:45.440
It was scored by Flyers forward Travis Konechny on Kings goalie Jack Campbell.

00:03:45.440 --> 00:03:48.839
It was at even strength, so there were five skaters on the ice for each team.

00:03:48.839 --> 00:03:52.440
It wasn't like a penalty situation or anything weird like that.

00:03:52.440 --> 00:03:55.259
It was right in front of the net, about 18 feet away.

00:03:55.259 --> 00:03:59.399
It was a wrist shot, and it caused the Flyers to go up 2-0.

00:03:59.399 --> 00:04:03.960
And in particular, with this labeled shot location, I have a little orange dot right

00:04:03.960 --> 00:04:09.279
where the trackers say the shot was.

00:04:09.279 --> 00:04:11.880
But what is the play-by-play data hiding?

00:04:11.880 --> 00:04:15.520
And it's worth knowing what are the strengths and limitations of our data.

00:04:15.520 --> 00:04:20.600
So first of all, actually, it's really nice that they labeled the shot for us, but frankly,

00:04:20.600 --> 00:04:24.760
the angle looks a bit off, which is definitely plausible because these shots are manually

00:04:24.760 --> 00:04:25.760
tracked.

00:04:25.760 --> 00:04:29.679
I say for now because the NHL has promised that they're going to implement tracking data

00:04:29.679 --> 00:04:35.019
this year, which will probably affect that.

00:04:35.019 --> 00:04:40.559
But for now, we can assume there is recording bias to some extent with these shot locations.

00:04:40.559 --> 00:04:47.119
So if we look back at this, kind of looking at where Travis Konechny is, I probably would

00:04:47.119 --> 00:04:49.279
have labeled the shot a little bit to the right.

00:04:49.279 --> 00:04:54.420
So we can say the distance maybe looks pretty good, but the angle is a bit off.

00:04:54.420 --> 00:04:59.519
So if we're making any models with that data, that's something to keep in mind.

00:04:59.519 --> 00:05:03.320
It's also worth noting that before the goal happened, Konechny was set up with a great

00:05:03.320 --> 00:05:06.480
quick pass that he was able to handle right away.

00:05:06.480 --> 00:05:10.720
If the pass wasn't as good, he might not have gotten as good of a shot off.

00:05:10.720 --> 00:05:11.920
He was also wide open.

00:05:11.920 --> 00:05:17.339
There wasn't any defenders in his immediate vicinity, and there were two players screening

00:05:17.339 --> 00:05:18.339
the net.

00:05:18.339 --> 00:05:19.799
Again, we can see it right here.

00:05:19.799 --> 00:05:23.880
So that probably gave the goalies some trouble.

00:05:23.880 --> 00:05:27.760
So all of that is to say there's a lot of stuff we know about the shot.

00:05:27.760 --> 00:05:29.720
There's a lot of stuff that we don't know.

00:05:29.720 --> 00:05:35.440
Probably if we incorporate all of this stuff that we can't see in the play-by-play data,

00:05:35.440 --> 00:05:40.480
it's probably a more dangerous shot than we would be able to estimate.

00:05:40.480 --> 00:05:46.160
But let's try it anyway, see what we can come up with.

00:05:46.160 --> 00:05:49.519
So unblocked shots.

00:05:49.519 --> 00:05:52.959
Blocked shots are like if you shoot and I stand in front of you and it hits me, and

00:05:52.959 --> 00:05:55.920
I get hurt real bad, but it doesn't go near the net.

00:05:55.920 --> 00:06:02.559
So unblocked shots that actually make it to the net at 5v5 have scored about 6% of the

00:06:02.559 --> 00:06:04.160
time this season.

00:06:04.160 --> 00:06:07.920
But I think TK, Travis Konechny's shot, was better than that.

00:06:07.920 --> 00:06:11.640
So how can we quantify this?

00:06:11.640 --> 00:06:16.720
And this is where I'm going to introduce expected goals to all of you and say that all of you

00:06:16.720 --> 00:06:21.200
can do this right now, because it's worth contextualizing shots with all this information

00:06:21.200 --> 00:06:27.640
that we have by turning them, instead of saying all of them are equal, we can start to estimate

00:06:27.640 --> 00:06:32.279
the probability of scoring for each shot.

00:06:32.279 --> 00:06:35.600
And everyone with a possible understanding of hockey, which I've just given to you right

00:06:35.600 --> 00:06:41.279
now, and R, which I hope a lot of you I think have come in with that knowledge, can build

00:06:41.279 --> 00:06:45.079
an expected goals model right now.

00:06:45.079 --> 00:06:46.079
These are facts.

00:06:46.079 --> 00:06:47.880
The opinion is that this is a fun thing to do.

00:06:47.880 --> 00:06:52.980
So you'll just have to take my word for it on that.

00:06:52.980 --> 00:06:56.320
And before I go any further, it's definitely worth noting that this is not some idea that

00:06:56.320 --> 00:06:57.880
I came up with.

00:06:57.880 --> 00:07:03.559
Expected goals has been a stat in the hockey analytics community for quite a while.

00:07:03.559 --> 00:07:08.320
And there have been a lot of really smart researchers to take a crack at this.

00:07:08.320 --> 00:07:13.559
And I can't go through all of their write-ups, but this is just to say that none of the ideas

00:07:13.559 --> 00:07:19.079
that follow are brand new or uniquely mine or anything like that.

00:07:19.079 --> 00:07:23.899
The stuff I do claim is my ggplot theme and talking about my favorite players, that's

00:07:23.899 --> 00:07:27.779
all me.

00:07:27.779 --> 00:07:30.579
And so I was talking about the play-by-play data.

00:07:30.579 --> 00:07:34.980
It's worth looking into, you know, where are we finding that?

00:07:34.980 --> 00:07:36.899
The short answer is the NHL.

00:07:36.899 --> 00:07:42.399
The longer answer is that a lot of people have put a lot of work into scraping NHL data

00:07:42.399 --> 00:07:44.179
and cleaning it.

00:07:44.179 --> 00:07:47.299
One of these people is Peter Tanner from moneypuck.com.

00:07:47.299 --> 00:07:53.059
So I give him a lot of credit for making this data really easily available for everyone.

00:07:53.059 --> 00:07:58.100
Because he scrapes NHL data every single day and shares season-level CSVs of every

00:07:58.100 --> 00:08:03.420
unblocked shot and all of the associated play-by-play information.

00:08:03.420 --> 00:08:08.420
And so for the purposes of this talk, we're going to use the information from 2017 to

00:08:08.420 --> 00:08:09.420
present.

00:08:09.420 --> 00:08:13.019
So, like, two and a half seasons, the most recent ones.

00:08:13.019 --> 00:08:17.019
And there is a lot of stuff that he did for us that I didn't want to do, so thank you

00:08:17.019 --> 00:08:18.700
so much, Peter.

00:08:18.700 --> 00:08:24.179
Including that he labeled shot types such as rush shots, rebounds, et cetera.

00:08:24.179 --> 00:08:30.220
So for example, the play-by-play won't say rebound, but you know that if the shot happened

00:08:30.220 --> 00:08:35.859
within two seconds of a previous shot, that that was probably a rebound.

00:08:35.859 --> 00:08:39.059
He also adjusted XY coordinates for recording bias.

00:08:39.059 --> 00:08:44.619
So I mentioned that these shot locations are manually tracked by, you know, a consistent

00:08:44.619 --> 00:08:47.619
group of people at each arena.

00:08:47.619 --> 00:08:53.820
So the recording bias has some consistent patterns based on the arena that you're in.

00:08:53.820 --> 00:08:57.659
So there are adjustments for that.

00:08:57.659 --> 00:09:02.460
And in general, cleaned it up, cross-referenced it, made sure that it was nice and ready to

00:09:02.460 --> 00:09:04.979
be very tidily analyzed by us.

00:09:04.979 --> 00:09:09.260
So again, shout out to him.

00:09:09.260 --> 00:09:12.260
This is the big code chunk that I'm sharing.

00:09:12.260 --> 00:09:15.260
It's not a complicated model or anything, but I really did want to share this to show

00:09:15.260 --> 00:09:24.700
like this is literally how easy it is to get NHL shot data in your RStudio instance and

00:09:24.700 --> 00:09:27.299
start to analyze it.

00:09:27.299 --> 00:09:34.020
And all I did was write a function to download the CSVs on his website and then use a bit

00:09:34.020 --> 00:09:41.219
of purr to map that to the most, three most recent seasons.

00:09:41.219 --> 00:09:43.260
And then I love the janitor package.

00:09:43.260 --> 00:09:46.460
I love clean underscore names.

00:09:46.460 --> 00:09:47.820
I love like snake case.

00:09:47.820 --> 00:09:49.659
I can't look at anything else anymore.

00:09:49.659 --> 00:09:52.179
So there you go.

00:09:52.179 --> 00:09:53.380
And I'll be tweeting this out later.

00:09:53.380 --> 00:09:58.820
So don't think you have to like write this down right now or anything like that.

00:09:58.820 --> 00:10:02.460
The first thing we can do before we get back to expected goals, heat maps.

00:10:02.460 --> 00:10:04.299
Everyone loves heat maps.

00:10:04.299 --> 00:10:10.900
So there is also code available to essentially make your own rink in ggplot.

00:10:11.580 --> 00:10:18.380
So I used that here to make a heat map of just all the unblocked shots in this data

00:10:18.380 --> 00:10:21.260
and where they were taken.

00:10:21.260 --> 00:10:24.619
And you can see they're generally taken closer to the net.

00:10:24.619 --> 00:10:27.780
I also made a heat map of the goals.

00:10:27.780 --> 00:10:32.380
And actually this alone can also tell you that, you know, shot location matters because

00:10:32.380 --> 00:10:36.500
if it didn't matter, if all shots were created equal, these heat maps would look the same.

00:10:36.500 --> 00:10:40.020
But clearly you can see that shots closer to the net are more dangerous, which also

00:10:40.140 --> 00:10:44.700
just makes sense like logically.

00:10:44.700 --> 00:10:50.380
The first thing we can do as kind of a really lazy baseline thing is just look at distance

00:10:50.380 --> 00:10:52.940
because I feel like that's something that's really important.

00:10:52.940 --> 00:10:58.059
And we can just use a logistic regression with a polynomial term and just estimate the

00:10:58.059 --> 00:11:03.700
probability of scoring a goal based on the absolute distance to the net.

00:11:03.700 --> 00:11:05.940
So the X axis there is shot distance.

00:11:05.940 --> 00:11:08.799
The Y axis is the probability.

00:11:08.799 --> 00:11:14.239
And we can see that just based on this one feature, your estimate can be anywhere from

00:11:14.239 --> 00:11:21.559
near 0% to near upwards of 20% if you're really close to the net.

00:11:21.559 --> 00:11:27.799
The slightly less lazy thing to do would be to use something like XGBoost and also incorporate

00:11:27.799 --> 00:11:32.719
shot angle, shot type, time and distance from the last event.

00:11:32.719 --> 00:11:35.479
And also not assume linearity.

00:11:35.479 --> 00:11:40.159
We can do some cross validation to choose the number of boosting rounds.

00:11:40.159 --> 00:11:44.179
And I always feel like whenever I talk about machine learning, I make it sound really simple

00:11:44.179 --> 00:11:45.179
and unimpressive.

00:11:45.179 --> 00:11:49.640
And I know you're not supposed to do that, which is why I've incorporated these images

00:11:49.640 --> 00:11:56.359
from Google searches of machine learning of like big brains and lots of nodes and stuff.

00:11:56.359 --> 00:11:58.320
So that is actually it.

00:11:58.320 --> 00:12:00.760
It's not the simple thing that I just said.

00:12:00.760 --> 00:12:05.460
Imagine that.

00:12:05.460 --> 00:12:10.539
And when we're talking about variable inclusion, it's worth really thinking about it.

00:12:10.539 --> 00:12:16.700
Because frankly, we're not working with big data here.

00:12:16.700 --> 00:12:22.900
There's not that many shots even when you're going over multiple seasons.

00:12:22.900 --> 00:12:27.820
And so I don't think this is the type of problem that requires like a kitchen sink approach

00:12:27.820 --> 00:12:32.020
of just like tossing in all the variables and seeing what sticks.

00:12:32.020 --> 00:12:37.219
I think it's worth it to kind of rely on some domain knowledge as well and think about

00:12:37.219 --> 00:12:41.580
what should be important, things like shot distance, shot angle, and what might not be

00:12:41.580 --> 00:12:43.140
as important.

00:12:43.140 --> 00:12:46.340
So I'm not including like score state.

00:12:46.340 --> 00:12:50.460
Because I can't think of a reason why after adjusting for everything else we already know

00:12:50.460 --> 00:12:56.479
about a shot, like the distance, angle, type, et cetera, I can't think of a compelling reason

00:12:56.479 --> 00:13:01.859
why it would matter that you took that shot if you were up two or if you were down three

00:13:01.859 --> 00:13:04.299
or whatever else.

00:13:04.299 --> 00:13:10.340
And fortunately, this has also been confirmed by previous expected goals research.

00:13:10.340 --> 00:13:14.419
You know, researchers that have included score state have found that it's like not really

00:13:14.419 --> 00:13:15.940
that important.

00:13:15.940 --> 00:13:19.659
So it's good to hear that confirmation.

00:13:19.659 --> 00:13:21.820
You could also include shooters and goalies.

00:13:21.820 --> 00:13:26.340
And I would say that it is important to know who was the goalie for the shot, who was the

00:13:26.340 --> 00:13:28.859
person who was shooting the puck.

00:13:28.859 --> 00:13:33.739
But you know, once you incorporate them as variables, you have to make decisions about

00:13:33.739 --> 00:13:38.260
sort of model structures and especially what you're going to do about players who have

00:13:38.260 --> 00:13:39.260
really small samples.

00:13:39.260 --> 00:13:44.280
You know, if they've only shot the puck five times, you know, are we going to regress them

00:13:44.280 --> 00:13:45.280
to the mean?

00:13:45.280 --> 00:13:46.619
How are we going to do that, et cetera?

00:13:46.619 --> 00:13:51.500
So for the sake of simplicity, I'm going to evaluate shooters and goalies by their residuals

00:13:51.500 --> 00:13:57.020
in this model and limit it to players with enough of a sample size that we feel comfortable

00:13:57.020 --> 00:14:01.140
evaluating them.

00:14:01.140 --> 00:14:06.140
And just really quick, some variable importance metrics from the XGBoost model.

00:14:06.140 --> 00:14:09.780
We can see shot distance is the most important one by far.

00:14:09.780 --> 00:14:16.700
And actually even the second most important is also just a component of shot distance.

00:14:16.700 --> 00:14:20.700
So really that is what matters, which I think makes a lot of sense.

00:14:20.700 --> 00:14:26.020
The type of shot and like whether it was a defender or forward matters a lot less.

00:14:26.020 --> 00:14:30.500
I think especially the fact of like position not mattering, probably what's happening is

00:14:30.500 --> 00:14:36.380
that's being incorporated in the shot distance variables because defenders tend to take shots

00:14:36.380 --> 00:14:37.979
much further away from the net.

00:14:37.979 --> 00:14:42.979
So you're probably seeing that effect there as well.

00:14:42.979 --> 00:14:50.299
So I love fitting smooths to glance at calibration in addition to looking at sort of standard

00:14:50.299 --> 00:14:51.700
evaluation metrics.

00:14:51.700 --> 00:14:57.539
So here I have three models, the logistic model, my XGBoost model, and also the MoneyPuck

00:14:57.539 --> 00:15:03.299
data includes Peter Tanner's expected goals model as well, so we can compare that.

00:15:03.299 --> 00:15:07.940
And so the X axis is the fitted expected goal value.

00:15:07.940 --> 00:15:12.780
The Y axis is, I mean, it's the indicator of whether it was a goal.

00:15:12.780 --> 00:15:18.460
And then as we fit a smooth, it should be on line Y equals X if it's really well calibrated.

00:15:18.460 --> 00:15:23.780
You can see that for the logistic model, you can barely see it because it's just kind

00:15:23.780 --> 00:15:30.020
of on Y equals X from zero to 25% basically, which is saying that like it's well calibrated,

00:15:30.020 --> 00:15:32.940
but obviously limited in a lot of ways.

00:15:32.940 --> 00:15:37.460
It doesn't have information to call any shots super dangerous.

00:15:37.460 --> 00:15:41.700
The XGBoost model does a bit better in that respect, although some of the really high

00:15:41.700 --> 00:15:48.140
fitted values are becoming goals like less than you'd expect.

00:15:48.140 --> 00:15:52.979
MoneyPuck also strays a little bit once you get to the really high values, but there honestly

00:15:52.979 --> 00:15:57.900
are much fewer shots in those categories.

00:15:57.900 --> 00:15:59.299
Some more model comparisons.

00:15:59.299 --> 00:16:05.460
So I always like to make the point, this is a problem that has a lot of class imbalance.

00:16:05.460 --> 00:16:10.820
So I could stand here and tell you like, oh, my accuracy is like 95% or whatever, and that

00:16:10.820 --> 00:16:12.260
would sound so good.

00:16:12.260 --> 00:16:20.260
But all I did was just say that no shot will ever become a goal, which goals do happen

00:16:20.260 --> 00:16:21.260
sometimes.

00:16:21.260 --> 00:16:26.940
So we can look to things like log loss and compare it to the situation where we say all

00:16:26.940 --> 00:16:29.780
shots are equally dangerous.

00:16:29.780 --> 00:16:33.419
We can compare that to our logistic model with the one feature.

00:16:33.419 --> 00:16:35.919
We can compare that to the XGBoost model.

00:16:35.919 --> 00:16:38.580
And here I'm using the cross validation predictions.

00:16:38.580 --> 00:16:47.940
So rest assured that these predictions have not looked at the data of that shot in question

00:16:47.940 --> 00:16:49.859
that is being predicted.

00:16:49.859 --> 00:16:56.979
And also, again, the MoneyPuck model, which is a nice benchmark for comparison as well.

00:16:56.979 --> 00:17:01.219
And you look at log loss, you look at area under the curve, you can see that basically

00:17:01.219 --> 00:17:07.359
what it comes down to is just distance alone will get you most of the way there.

00:17:07.359 --> 00:17:12.520
The XGBoost model with a few additional features gets you a little bit further.

00:17:12.520 --> 00:17:18.319
And then probably whatever Peter did for his model was a little bit better.

00:17:18.319 --> 00:17:23.839
But I think it's great that I was able to get close to his results in, frankly, like

00:17:23.839 --> 00:17:24.839
a day of work.

00:17:24.839 --> 00:17:27.359
So calling that a win.

00:17:27.359 --> 00:17:34.319
And then also to bring things full circle, we looked at Travis Konechny's goal earlier,

00:17:34.319 --> 00:17:40.239
and we knew that it wouldn't be right to assume that it had the same probability of

00:17:40.239 --> 00:17:44.180
scoring as the average shot.

00:17:44.180 --> 00:17:47.319
So that would be about 5.7%.

00:17:47.319 --> 00:17:52.079
If we incorporate the shot distance and look at the logistic model, we would assume about

00:17:52.079 --> 00:17:54.359
a 10% chance of scoring.

00:17:54.359 --> 00:17:57.680
The XGBoost model goes a little bit higher, closer to 12%.

00:17:57.680 --> 00:18:02.040
And then MoneyPuck's model, I think, does the best job by saying it's 15%.

00:18:02.040 --> 00:18:05.719
And then, you know, if we have additional features, maybe from tracking data or something

00:18:05.719 --> 00:18:11.619
like that, we might even say that it's more dangerous than that.

00:18:11.619 --> 00:18:16.479
And lastly, because I said expected and unexpected goals, so here's what I mean by unexpected

00:18:16.479 --> 00:18:17.479
goals.

00:18:17.479 --> 00:18:20.040
So we can use this to evaluate shooters.

00:18:20.040 --> 00:18:27.040
And what we do essentially, and I have some nice tidyverse verbs there, we can for each

00:18:27.079 --> 00:18:32.479
shooter and all the unblocked shots that they have in this dataset, we can calculate their

00:18:32.479 --> 00:18:35.920
expected shooting percentage based on our expected goals model.

00:18:35.920 --> 00:18:40.000
We can calculate their actual shooting percentage based on the goals that they scored and the

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:41.400
difference.

00:18:41.400 --> 00:18:46.280
And then once we filter down to enough shots that we don't have really wonky results, you

00:18:46.280 --> 00:18:51.319
know, these are the top six for the timeframe that I looked at.

00:18:51.319 --> 00:18:57.939
And so we can see Brett Connelly, Logan Couture, Berkovsky, Dreisaitl, Kopitar, Panarin.

00:18:57.939 --> 00:19:05.400
These guys, conditioning on where they were shooting, the angle, et cetera, have scored

00:19:05.400 --> 00:19:09.079
at the highest, you know, percentage relative to that.

00:19:09.079 --> 00:19:14.579
And so that is interesting from a player evaluation standpoint.

00:19:14.579 --> 00:19:16.560
So with that, that's all I have for you guys.

00:19:16.560 --> 00:19:17.739
Thank you so much for listening.

00:19:17.739 --> 00:19:23.260
Thank you again to Moneypuck and some of my other friends, Manny, Micah, Luke, and Josh, and all

00:19:23.260 --> 00:19:25.660
the other researchers I've read and cited.

00:19:25.660 --> 00:19:29.339
I'll be tweeting this out at NNStats, so you can find me there.

00:19:29.339 --> 00:19:31.140
And I'll take a few questions if there's time.

00:19:39.020 --> 00:19:40.979
We do have time for one question.

00:19:40.979 --> 00:19:44.219
How is the information communicated to the coaches and players?

00:19:44.300 --> 00:19:49.900
Are there analytics that can be provided mid-game that leads to strategy changes?

00:19:49.900 --> 00:19:52.540
This is actually something that I'm curious about myself.

00:19:52.540 --> 00:19:56.140
And frankly, you know, I'll mention a little bit of my day job here.

00:19:56.140 --> 00:20:01.859
Because football is so discreet in the plays and stuff like that, like, there are definitely

00:20:01.859 --> 00:20:07.540
materials that we can provide saying, like, if you see this situation, this is what you

00:20:07.540 --> 00:20:08.540
should do.

00:20:08.540 --> 00:20:10.780
But frankly, I'm curious about it myself.

00:20:10.780 --> 00:20:14.660
In a hockey context, what are the sort of adjustments that you can make in-game?

00:20:14.660 --> 00:20:19.660
Frankly, a lot of the research that I've done has been more on the player evaluation side

00:20:19.660 --> 00:20:20.660
of things.

00:20:20.660 --> 00:20:23.540
So just trying to build up the best roster and then kind of be like, all right, go do

00:20:23.540 --> 00:20:24.540
your best.

00:20:24.540 --> 00:20:27.660
That's all the time we have, unfortunately.

00:20:27.660 --> 00:20:28.180
Thank you again.

